Protein Structure Analysis

Heat Shock Proteins

Heat shock proteins are highly conserved and present in all organisms. Zi, L. & Srivastava, P., Heat Shock Proteins, Curr Protoc Immunol. (Feb. 2004). Selected heat shock proteins, also known as chaperones, are involved in protein folding and unfolding, assembly of protein complexes, transport and sorting of proteins into the correct cellular compartments, cell-cycle control and signaling, and protection of cells against stress and apoptosis. See Id. The four proteins selected have pairwise sequence identity less than 50%, are all less than 300 residues, and have images taken using x-ray crystallography with a resolution greater than 1.9, and are all small heat shock proteins (sHSPs). Sun, Y. & MacRae, T.H., Small Heat Shock Proteins: molecular and chaperone function. Cell Mol. Life Sci., pp. 2460-76 (Nov. 2005). As heat shock proteins, they associate with nuclei, cytoskeleton, and membranes, and as molecular chaperones they bind partially denatured proteins. See Id.

The first protein is Heat Shock Protein 17.7 found in the extremophilic bacterium Deinococcus radiodurans

(image resolution 2.677 A, x-ray diffraction, 102 residues).


Taken from RCSB Protein Data Bank: https://www.rcsb.org/structure/4FEI. Bepperling, A. et al.,
Proc.Natl.Acad.Sci.USA (2012).


The second protein analyzed was Heat Shock Protein 20.1 found in the thermophilic archaeon Sulfolobus solfataricus

(image resolution 2.4 A, x-ray diffraction, 180 residues).


Taken from RCSB Protein Data Bank:https://www.rcsb.org/structure/4rzk. Liang, L. & Yun, C.H., Biochem. Biophys. Res. Commun. (2015)


The third protein analyzed was Heat Shock Protein-A found in the proteobacteria Xanthomonas axonopodis

(image resolution 2.15 A, x-ray diffraction, 206 residues).


Taken from RCSB Protein Data Bank: https://www.rcsb.org/structure/3gt6. Hilario, E. et al., J. Mol. Biol. (2011)

The final protein analyzed was Heat Shock Protein 40 found in brewer's yeast Saccaromyces cerevisiae

(image resolution 2.7 A, x-ray diffraction, 170 residues)

Taken from RCSB Protein Data Bank: https://www.rcsb.org/structure/1C3G. Sha, B., et al., Structure (2000).

RESULTS SUMMARY

INPUT SEQUENCES


PHYLOGENETIC TREE

Consistent with the literature, we see a close evolutionary relationship between all four small heat shock proteins examined. Given the importance of heat shock proteins and chaperones in sustaining biological life, this is not surprising. To further investigate the relationship between the four proteins, we can conduct a secondary structure and motif analysis.

HSP 17.7



Secondary structure analysis completed using: Network Protein Sequence Analysis, TIBS

HSP 20.1



Secondary structure analysis completed using: Network Protein Sequence Analysis, TIBS
2000 March Vol. 25, No 3 [291]: 147-150 Combet C., Blanchet C., Geourion C. and Deleage


Each of the proteins show significant alpha helices, random coils, and extended strands. 'Alpha helices are more robust to mutations than beta strands.' Abrusan G. & Marsh J., PLOS Computational Biology (December 9, 2016).  We see a significant presence of alpha helices in all 4 proteins. Moreover, we also see a significant presence of extended strands. Let's look at another multiple sequence alignment, but this time on which shows consensus secondary structure information.


Multiple sequence alignment completed using: PROMALS3D: a tool for multiple sequence and structure alignment. Jimin Pei, Bong-Hyun Kim and Nick V. Grishin. Nucleic Acids Res. 2008 36(7):2295-2300.
Available at: http://prodata.swmed.edu/promals3d/promals3d.php

This shows a significant presence of beta strands, and an alpha helix in the first alignment (beta strands are denoted as "e" and alpha helices as "h"). This is consistent with the secondary structure analysis above, which shows a significant presence of extended strands.


MOTIF ANALYSIS

HSP 17.7

 

Motif analysis completed using: MOTIF Search, GenomeNet, Japan, available at: https://www.genome.jp/tools/motif/.


Here we see the prevalence of the alpha-crystallin domain. Alpha-crystallin has chaperone properties, including the ability to mitigate the precipitation of denatured proteins and defend cells against stress.  Augusteyn RC, Alpha-crystallin: a review of its structure and function, Clin Exp Optom. 87(6), 356-66 (2004).


HSP 20.1


Motif analysis completed using: MOTIF Search, GenomeNet, Japan, available at: https://www.genome.jp/tools/motif/.


HSP-A


Motif analysis completed using: MOTIF Search, GenomeNet, Japan, available at: https://www.genome.jp/tools/motif/.


HSP 40


Motif analysis completed using: MOTIF Search, GenomeNet, Japan, available at: https://www.genome.jp/tools/motif/.


We see the alpha-crystallin domain in all proteins except HSP 40. We also see the CS domain in HSP 20.1 and the DnaJ C terminal domain in HSP 40. The CS domain overlaps with the homologous HSP-20 like chaperone superfamily. CS Domain (IPR007052), EMBL-EBI, Wellcome Genome Campus, Hixton, Cambridgeshire, UK, available at: http://www.ebi.ac.uk/interpro/entry/IPR007052. Likewise, the DnaJ C terminal domain is also associated with the chaperone family.

Structural (multiple) alignments (to obtain structure similarity data) were done using amino acid sequence data in: T-coffee, ExPASy Bioinformatics Resource Portal,
Swiss Bioinformatics Institute, Available at: https://tcoffee.vital-it.ch/apps/tcoffee/do:expresso


Correlation between structural similarity and percent sequence identity for multiple sequence/structure alignments of whole proteins. As shown, we see a linear positive correlation between structural similarity (as measure by RMSD) and percent sequence identity.



Correlation between structural similarity and percent sequence identity for multiple sequence/structure alignments of protein fragments. As shown, we do not find the correlations which exist above. This is because the upper threshold of sequence identity values are very close to the structural similarity scores, hence, the cluster of points (roughly) between 70 and 90 (on the x-axis) and the cluster around 20. It should be noted that the fragments were generated by a pairwise sequence alignment algorithm, and thus we would not necessarily expect to find correlations.  Moreover, we could expect a similar lack of correlation if we were to use the motif or secondary structure sequence data for our plots. The reason is quite simple, we see many of the same domains and secondary structure profiles in all four of the small heat shock proteins under investigation, suggesting an evolutionary relationship and a similar clustering of the data that we see in the plot shown below.
